statement:
A toxic chemical has been spilled somewhere on a 100 km stretch of
highway. The probability that the spill occurred within $x$ km of the
factory is shown in the panel below.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{Math_Exam_Resources_Courses_MATH103_April_2010_Question_3_(a)_picture1_top.png}
\caption{Math\_Exam\_Resources\_Courses\_MATH103\_April\_2010\_Question\_3\_(a)\_picture1\_top.png}
\end{figure}

(a) Plot the probability density $p(x)$ for the location of the spill in
the grid provided. (You do not need to provide a scale on the $y$ axis.)

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{Math_Exam_Resources_Courses_MATH103_April_2010_Question_3_(a)_picture1_bottom.png}
\end{description}

sols:
The derivative \emph{p(x)} is zero whenever \emph{F(x)} is flat, and
\emph{p(x)} is positive whenever \emph{F(x)} is increasing.

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{Math_Exam_Resources_Courses_MATH103_April_2010_Question_3_(a)_solution_to_3a.png}
\end{description}

hints:
Since

\begin{align*}F(x) = \int_0^x p(s)\,ds\end{align*}

the Fundamental theorem of calculus says that

\begin{align*}F'(x) = p(x).\end{align*}

Hence you are asked to plot the derivative of the given function
\emph{F(x)}.
